{
  "number": 1743,
  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/1743",
  "title": "How to implement search for facet values in react-instantsearch",
  "body": "Goal of search for facet values: allow a user to search for specific values of a facet and select them. \r\n\r\nWhat's follow is a start to talk about our implementation of the search for facet values in react-instantsearch:\r\n\r\n**1. Connectors**\r\n\r\na. Provide a `searchForFacetValues`function as a prop (like we do for `refine`) that will be in charge to trigger a search for facet values. If a connector must provide this feature, it will need to implement it by returning both the facetName and the query to use. \r\n\r\nb. add to the `getProvidedProps` function, a fifth parameters called for example `facetValues` which will contains the results of the search for facet values. (Those results will be stored into our store).\r\nWe can have an object with the following form: \r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst facetValues = {\r\n  attributeName (the facetName): \r\n  {\r\n      items: facetHits,\r\n      query\r\n  } \r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe goal is to be able to retrieve the results inside the `getProvidedProps` function and format them to be used by the component (by returning along with `items` and `currentRefinement` a new `facetHits` prop). \r\n\r\nquestion: should we do that directly on the connectors that will support search for facet values, or should we create new connectors? \r\n\r\n**2. Widgets**\r\n\r\nSame question as connectors: should we provide an option to activate the search for facet values inside our default widget or just create new ones (starting by the refinementList)? \r\n\r\nWhat do you think?\r\n \r\n",
